animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.=========================================================
Please contact app@aarfhouston.org for more information about this dog. You can apply online by clicking on Application .
Puppies that are under 4 months old cannot be adopted outside of our Veterinary Service area. Please call for specific locations. Children under 8 years old often are not a good match for our puppies and dogs. In order to protect both, your child and our rescued dogs/puppies from harm, we seldom if ever adopt to families with young children.
Once your application is approved, we will schedule a meet and greet at one of our adoption events. Thank you for considering a rescue! The adoption fee includes vaccinations, Bordetella, de-worming, rabies, spay/neuter and microchip. There is a an additional $12.99 fee for Home Again for a lifetime registration of the microchip.
Puppies cannot be adopted outside of the Houston area until they are spay/neutered after they are 4 months old. It is against the law in the State of Texas for a rescue not to be sterilized so we have to make sure it gets completed and that we have record of it.
NOTE: In our bios, we provide information based on our volunteer's experience with a particular dog; such as temperament, training, and ability to get along with others.
AARF is a 501(c)3 Non Profit, all breed, no kill organization. Our group is always in need of donations in order to continue to give the needed medical care to our rescues. Adoption fees do not begin to cover all of the medical costs. Any donation , no matter how small is a big help and is greatly appreciated. Please help us to continue to help them. Thank you.
animal.name: Sweet Pea

animal.description:
Meet Sky

This gorgeous girl is beautiful and smart. You can have it all in a companion with this beauty!  I love to go on walks, play outside and cuddle with my owners. I am good at listening to commands. I know sit, stay, down, come and no!  I know you are loving me because I am so smart. Let me share some more about myself- I am potty trained, so I will not ruin Grandma’s antique rug you might have. I do good  with a doggie door as well. If I am not let out, I could have the occasional accident, I can’t hold It for long times. My favorite part of the day is with my owner when I get belly rubs, rubs behind the ear (this makes me doze off) and when we get to cuddle. I will also be your companion for watching TV. I love movies, sports, and HGTV. Anything you watch, I love to watch too!  Sometimes I do get skittish with strange noises, so be patient with me in your home until I learn those sounds, and I may give the occasional bark. I get along great with other dogs, I just need some time to to get to know them. I am not sure about cats, I have not been around them. I am leash trained, and love walks at sunrise or sunset  I do not like being confined in the crate- I am so good on my own, that I do not need to be in a crate. I get scared being locked up. I also do not like being an outside dog- being inside is my favorite- please do not put me outside with a dog house. I am a very smart and beautiful girl and I am looking for my fur- ever home. 

We have a family of Sheppards! Mommy sky is about 1-2 years old. She had a little of 6 babies. We have the daddy also! Shaggy(adopted)They are both amazing dogs. The mom and babies are ore adoption only. We are taking applications to start the process but will not be available to go to their new home until babies are winged. But they will find homes quick so put your application in!

animal.description:
This is Sasha! Female. 42.2lbs. Very young/puppy like in behavior. Friendly, but still skittish if anyone moves to quickly, but once she knows shes in good hands she does wonderfully. We know she's been mistreated. Approx 8-9 months old, a stray female, Lab mix that wandered up on a property.

She runs like a gazelle. But she also calms down very easily. She's not hyper at all. She plays when it's time to play them come in and will settle down. She loves to give out kisses. She does well with other dogs and not right for cats. Alone, she would be wanting more attention and would require a stay-at-home or work-from-home individual.

She is learning manners and is housebroken. She will stand at the backdoor then look back at her human when she has to go. She is not good on a leash, but the foster is working with her to get used to one. She is crate trained. And prefers to be in it only for short periods. She will lay inside one, at times, with the door open. She is still puppy and will chew, but given a chew toy and other toys. She's easily corrected and redirected. Very eager to please and very smart and she knows how to open a door if it's not shut all the way.

She seems good with big dogs and dogs that are 20lbs & active. Sasha would thrive in a home with one or more dogs. She will require a private fenced in yard. She's active, playful, enjoys playing with a couple of other dogs, and will attach to her human quickly. She still needs a moment to trust people, but then she wants to be with them everywhere. This is why she needs a home with one or more dogs., so she gets to play & learn more about being a dog. Sasha understands the pack rules, never snaps back when others snap at her. She has no aggression, and is submissive.

If you are interested in giving a home to Sasha please go complete our online pre-adoption application http://www.southernskiesrescue.org/adoption-application

Sasha is fully medically vetted; spayed, up-to-date on prevention plus will be microchipped before going to her forever home.

This is our sweet boy Luke. He is a mellow guy who loves attention and loves to play in morning and sunbathe in the afternoon. We estimate him to be 4 years old and weighs around 60 lbs, he's a little short and hefty but don't let him fool you, this boy loves to run. He has the cutest baby face! If you are looking for a cuddle bug/couch potato, Luke is the quarantine buddy you're looking for.



BY APPOINTMENT ONLY

Please complete an application at https://kingsspca.org/adoption-1

This dog is available for adoption at the Kings SPCA Shelter - 9071 16 1/2 Ave. Lemoore, CA 93245.

We do NOT transfer or transport animals for adoption or foster, nor do we hold animals for your visit. Adoptions must be completed in person at our shelter.

Puppies and dogs must have a harness to leave the shelter after adoption. Please feel free to bring your own (it must fit properly) or you can purchase one from us at the time of adoption. We will provide a leash at no charge if you do not have one. We do not allow dogs to leave after adoption with a standard neck collar only.

Adoption fee’s are based upon age. 
For more information on fees, visit our webpage at www.kingsspca.org. 
For current specials, visit www.facebook.com/kingsspca.

All dog adoptions include:
Rabies Vaccination (if over 4 months at time of adoption)
DHPP (Combination Yearly Vaccination)
Spay/Neuter Surgery
Microchip

For more information on this dog please contact the Kings SPCA at :
e-mail: Halfwayhomeca@gmail.com
phone: 559-925-1630

animal.description: Adopter must be from the Denver area and have a fenced yard. Hunter, who is 5 yrs old, will need a few gradually increased visits in the potential adoptive home prior to adoption. Hunter is a dog with a lot to teach humans. He needs a family with experienced dog owners who have the patience and skills to look, listen, and learn. He has taught me that he can be ok with both men and women if they allow him to be slow and to have time to really gather his senses and access a new situation. Because Hunter is timid, he does not like to be reached for or approached suddenly and might try to bite if he is approached in this manner. He needs to know what is going to happen before it happens. We can only guess what happened to Hunter is his past to have instilled some fears. Since he came to my foster home, I have witnessed Hunter go from cautious, apprehensive, insecure, and protective to calm, trusting, gentle and relaxed - as long as he understands what is going to happen. Hunter will bark loudly at first meeting, and maybe even the second meeting. Once he has been allowed the time and space to settle and begin to feel comfortable, he will soften, attach, and seek close attention. He has shown that he can be a loyal companion, but he must feel his way first. Hunter is living in a multi foster-dog household with adults. But since he does have some territorial tendencies, surrounding food and possessions, it will be best for both Hunter and his new family to be an only dog. He seems able to go back and forth between the woman and man in the home, either lap is fine, but he has really taken favor to the man of the house. Hunter has not been tested with or exposed to cats. Please, no children for this dog. A fenced yard is a must! Hunter loves to be outdoors watching the birds, squirrels, and going on a backyard chase.

animal.description: Frida is a sweet senior who has lived outside all her life. At 10 years old, she now enjoys the comforts of an indoor home and is learning new manners for inside the house including potty training. A regular potty schedule is important for her. Frida has had a lot of change in her life recently, so it isnt surprising that she has some anxiety issues. She can take a while to adjust to living with other dogs and may have some squabbles with them. She soaks up love and attention from her people although it takes her longer to warm up to men. Frida cant get enough attention from her people which may be why she is slow to share that with other animals in the house. Fridas right eye was removed due to uncontrolled glaucoma, which you may not notice right away because she has the most amazing tan eyebrows. She has partial vision in her left eye and will need on-going eye medication for it. Frida navigates well, can get up on the furniture and never has a problem finding her person. Being with you and getting belly rubs are favorite pastimes, although she also enjoys chewing on her toys (and sometimes the laundry). Frida needs a quiet home with a yard and people who are home most of the day. Frida is learning a lot in her foster home, but gets nervous when picked up and car rides are scary. This sweet and silly girl is a loyal companion that will bring much love and laughter to her forever home.

animal.description: Harley is as sweet as he looks. He is perfectly house broken and knows the basic commands. He is also learning new ones. He wants nothing more than to be with his human, whether on the couch or hiking or camping. He loves his people and loves to snuggle! Harley needs to be an only dog. He aggressively attacks all other dogs immediately, even dogs he has met before. He has extreme separation anxiety. He must always be in a crate when left alone, otherwise he will engage in destructive behavior. He can be vocal when left alone in his crate and is distraught. He dislikes riding in the car and does best in a crate. He requires a yard with a privacy fence and no neighboring dogs. Harley needs a stay-at-home parent. Likes to Fetch, Leash Trained, Likes Toys, Lap Dog, Affectionate, Eager to Please, Must be only dog, Not Good with other Dogs, Adults only, Crate Trained (Est. DOB: 8/2011)

animal.description: Sadie is a very sweet and scared 2-year old girl of mixed breed (Dachshund & Terrier?) who tips the scales at 15 lbs. She is very afraid of meeting new people and needs someone who can deal with fear anxiety. Shes a dog who loves physical attention, and to snuggle with her peeps. She gets along fine with other dogs, eats well (dry food), and is mostly (but not quite) housebroken. She barks when she sees or hears people outside, but her barking isnt excessive. She loves to be outside, whether is hanging out in the backyard, or walking on a leash around the block. Shes a very fast runner, enjoys chasing squirrels in the back yard, and will even fetch a ball! Sadie is very fearful strangers, and she can act aggressively when she is frightened. Her behaviors include barking, growling, and biting. She needs to be restrained when introduced to new people until she learns to trust them. Sadie would do best with someone who can work with her on this, and manage her behaviors until she learns to be less fearful. Sadie will also do best where she has access to a secure yard where she can run and play. Sadie is a wonderful little dog who would bring joy to anyones home. She will make you smile with her antics, and will melt your heart with her big brown eyes. Shes a young, healthy girl who wants nothing more than to have a forever home of her own!

animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in dog who needs a new home. Adoption can be one of the most fulfilling experiences in your life and especially in the life of your new canine companion.

A note to those looking at CPR. We have no perfect dogs - but many of our dogs have proven to be perfect for a certain someone. Our job is to find those someone's. Our most successful adopters come to CPR not because they want a dog. They come to us because they want to give a dog a home. We urge all of our potential adopters not to fall in love with a picture. While we like to know what you like in looks, a dog is more than a pretty face. Our goal is to match you with the best possible pet for you and your home. We want to create furever families.

Our descriptions contain all that we know about this dog today. We'll update as more information is known.

Are you looking to adopt within the next 30 days? If so please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and complete the application. You'll find it in the menu on the left hand side. You'll also find a total listing of all our dogs available.

Just browsing but interested in poodles and poodle mixes? Please drop a note to applications@carolinapoodlerescue.org with your name, address and phone # and email. We'll add you to our mailing list.

thanks
the CPR Adoption team

Date into Rescue: 11/19/2020
Reason for being in rescue: Berto was seized as part of a local case. Carolina Poodle Rescue partnered with the shelter to help him and his brothers and sisters.
Foster location: Dreamweaver Farms, Pacolet SC
Special Needs? Berto was neutered on 11/23/20. He is now ready for his forever home.
Weight: 11.4 lbs
Height: 9 in
Spayed/Neutered: No

Adoption Fee: $200

Fence needed? No

What kind of home would be best for me? As adorable as he is, Berto is NOT for a first time dog owner. Berto is young, but has lived a lot of years in his short life. He requires an experienced owner that has patience and time to earn his trust. He would be happy as the only dog, or living with a confident dog that will teach him without overpowering him. Berto is not suited for a home with children. A more quiet routine is his speed.

What is my personality like? Berto was seized with a group of dogs as part of a local effort. We know very little about their past. Berto is a little shy, and doesn't fully understand what love means. Once he warms up, Berto wants to spend his entire day with his person. Berto comes from a home with lots of other dogs. He is absolutely fine in a pack. However, he'd be equally happy as the only dog.

Berto is a young dog with a ton of potential. His sassy smile screams bad to the bone, but his heart is made of gold. At the core, Berto is a young dog that lacks confidence. In a group of dogs, he gets picked on by more dominant dogs. He is slow to approach and absolutely does not want you to pick him up, but sit down and he jumps right into your lap for snuggles.

Berto loves to play. Toys have clearly been part of his past and he tosses toys around with enthusiasm. He also loves to snuggle in fuzzy blankets. We are certain this is the chihuahua in his DNA. He is crate trained and quiet for feeding. Like his siblings, Berto is really decompressing and learning and starting to come out of his shell. Underneath that somewhat timid shell is an absolute angel!

How do I act when I first meet new people? Timid and standoffish

Other tips and tidbits: Berto's estimated birthday is 11/13/2017

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

Please note - we do not ship dogs. If you are interested in adopting, please take a look at the distance between the foster home location and your location and make sure you are willing to make that trip. Most of our dogs are at our farm in Pacolet, South Carolina.

To apply, please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and visit the tab on the left that directions you to the online application.

Please note that when screening applications, we look at the entire home and then make suggestions based on what would be a good fit for your home. You are not being screened for a specific dog although we are looking to see what type of dog interests you - poodles or non poodles, color, age, etc. Others here may be a better fit for you. It is very difficult to get to know a living animal from a picture and a short description. Since we are constantly getting in new dogs, this may be a dog not in our listings yet. We want you to be very happy with your new companion and will make suggestions based on what you tell us about you.

Thank you for considering CPR.

animal.description: Radar is a 9 year old cocker/cavalier boy who was found drowning in a canal in southwest Miami Dade county. Thank goodness for a good samaritan that fished him out and saved his life!!! It is evident that Radar has suffered abuse throughout his life - he is deathly afraid of being grabbed by his neck or a leash being put on him so he must go to an adopter that is patient, has dog experience , and has a fenced in yard where Radar can go outside and romp around safely without issue- he does walk well on a leash once put on him but it is that initial move that he is scared of. Radar is very apprehensive of new people but will warm up to you once he knows you will not hurt him and he can trust you---he just needs time and patience and lots of love. This boy is also deaf so he will go to a home with NO KIDS that can come upon him and scare him. Once Radar knows he is safe he will follow you around and looks for attention and petting. If interested in adopting Radar please fill out an application at www.floridacockerrescue.org   ADOPTION FEE: $265.00

animal.description:
Willie, 8 mo., neutered, Border Collie mixWillie is free as a dog can safely be! This approx. 8 mo. Border Collie mix pup, is in Paso Robles. He's now neutered, has current vaccinations and micro-chipped.Willie was a stray in Kerman a couple months ago. Just a baby. It seemed he had no human experience. No leash experience and so frightened. Nice dog, but kinda feral.Willie didn't have a chance if he went into this little rural shelter. The director reached out to the best, Kalyn. She contacted me, explained and offered to keep Willie until he could get in here.Kalyn got him walking on a leash and follow her along without one. She says he's only a reliable as the dog he's running with, but we'll take it! There's lots of dogs that have good recall here, and we'll teach Willie!He's here now and great with my entire pack. He's a just kid! He's a little shy, but once he's on a leash he's your dog. He'll need some attention to get him comfortable, but he's happy and excited about life!I'm looking for a home with another dog though. Help show Willie the way! He'd be fine with kids, and possibly cats. He's very sweet.Willie's looking for a home - could it be yours?
Photos updated at: https://www.facebook.com/media/set/?vanity=cchdrescue.org&set=a.2724223784460350
Adoption fee is $350 and includes sterilization surgery, vaccinations, flea & tick abatement, worming, transportation to us, microchipping + chip registration. Also covers care for all the dogs while in rescue.
To download an application to meet Willie: http://cchdrescue.org/adoptionprocess.html or email: info@cchdrescue.org
Central Coast Herding Dog Rescue, is a Rescue Alliance partner, a federally recognized 501(c)3 non profit organization, dedicated to finding great dogs, great homes. County of San Luis Obispo Animal Service Operating Permit #C2649. Thank you for reading about Willie, and thanks for considering rescue! 12/31/20 10:52 AM

animal.description:
Hi this is Teddy and I am really hoping someone will open up their heart and their home for me. You see I spent most of my life on the other end of a chain until I got to go to Rescue. Fortunately I didn’t end up with heart worms but my foster mom has her work cut out for her getting me crate trained and housetrained and I‘ve really come along way. I can proudly say that I am both now! I have to admit I really don’t like to stay in the crate. I don’t mind sleeping there but I can’t wait for my play time and outside time. But then I love to come in and go to my crate because I know I get treats! I’m just so happy to be in a new place with new friends and lots of food and love that I get really excited! And they have toys and balls here! I didn’t know what those were but boy are they fun!

My favorite thing is eating as I was really underweight when I got here. I’m getting healthier now too. And my coat looks much better as I had really bad flea allergy but my fur is growing back in and it’s going to be lush and beautiful soon. I get along with most of my foster brothers and sisters but I had no social skills at all so they’re helping me and they have to be patient with me. Living on the end of the chain doesn’t do much for one’s personality. But I have really come along way on that too. I’m just getting better and better at everything every day. I just need the chance to prove myself.  Will you be the one that takes a chance on me? If so please fill out your application today! I will make you proud! 

Link to Application:
http://www.gsdrescuectx.com/adoption-application.html

animal.description:
Hi this is Louie  and I’m taking applications for my forever home.

I had a wonderful happy home but my little girl got cancer and since they had to have a completely sterile environment for her I had to go live outside. I guess that’s when I got Heartworms as they didn’t really have time for me anymore and I was outside all the time, and I guess they forgot to give me my prevention. My family said they still loved me but they just couldn’t care for me the way I needed to be cared for so they took me to the shelter. Then my life took a turn for the better when my foster mom came into it. I was not doing well at all in the shelter but the rescue saved me.

I’m getting healthier and they’re giving me medicine to help kill my heart worms. They will give my adopters the medicine and all the directions to keep doing this for me. I get to eat really well here too and my foster mom is giving me sardines in my food because I was also anemic. My coat is starting to get shinier and healthier again. I like it here but I would really like to have my own home again. I have a really unusual coloring for German Shepherd. I am chocolate and tan.  I think that makes me special! So if you would like to give me a second chance and come live with you I promise I will be a good boy and love you!

Link to Application:
http://www.gsdrescuectx.com/adoption-application.html

animal.description:
“The journey is more important to me now.  There’s no guarantee, no matter what.  We get one run in life.”  Well, except for those of us lucky to get a second chance and the journey is worth it if it ends with you as my forever home.  The name is Suki.  I am a 4 year old, 60 lbs, female Husky mix.  There is absolutely no question that I am the smartest of them all.  I know just about all the tricks in the book, sit, down, shake, roll over, jump, high five, crate, speak and sooo much more.  Not only that, I have already mastered all of that house and crate training business.  While I may spend most of my time laying back and hanging out, don’t think that I won’t sprint to the door for an exciting game of fetch.  I absolutely love fetch!  I’m good with other dogs, cats and older kids.  The leash is absolutely no problem for me but I need a fenced in yard. I am enrolled in some extra training classes at a local prison, I should be back around mid-February! With me being such a catch you’ll likely need to be “Fast and Furious” to get that application in, so don’t hesitate in filling out that application for me, Suki.  

My adoption fee is $150 and includes my spay/neuter, vaccinations, wellness exam, heartworm test, and microchip! If you're interested in meeting/adopting me, please visit www.rescueonespringfield.com/our-adoption-process/adoption-application/ and fill out the form! We do adopt out of state with vet references and video home check. *Adopter is responsible for coming to get the dog and returning the dog if the adoption does not work out* 

Don't forget to LIKE us on Facebook!-www.facebook.com/rescueonespringfield

*Remember, dogs are pack animals. Because of this, Rescue One does not adopt to outdoor-only homes. Pets are family and are not disposable.  Please make sure that you are 100% committed to a pet before considering adding one to your home.

animal.description:
Felix is a young male who we just rescued from a San Francisco, CA shelter.  He is currently living with his foster family in Southern California, and we are learning more about him. We think Felix is around one year old. He has lots of energy and loves playing with toys! He is goofy and loveable!

Felix is looking for a home that is patient, loving, and willing to help him learn manners and basic training.  He can be a little skiddish at first with strangers (especially men) and needs slow introductions to warm up to you. His new family should not have cats, but he may be ok with a female dog if the family is experienced and willing to separate and do slow and proper introductions. 

Felix says you can check out the rest of his profile here:
https://petlover.petstablished.com/pets/public/887005?awo=DC+Dogos%2C+Inc&widget=false

Dogos are a wonderful breed but we urge anyone interested to dig in and do a lot of research before deciding if they are a good fit for your home. They require a lot of attention and training with them never ends!  Boundaries must be enforced and they often need reminders as they push past boundaires you set! Dogos are loving, kind and gentle but don't mistake that for weakness because they are equally powerful and intense as well! Everyone in the home must be on board with having a dogo and play a major role in their daily routines and training. Yes it is work, but the rewards are ten-fold! Lazy homes don't work for dogos as they need stimulation, exercise, and lots of attention too during their younger years.  Our goal in rescue is to be as transparent as we can about each and every dog plus make sure new families really understand the needs of a dogo!

I am good boy looking for my forever home. Everyone I meet falls in love with my cute, sweet face! I went on a vacation to a fosters house. I was such a good boy, I had no accidents, and was on good behavior the whole time. I really just wanted to cuddle mostly, with some nice walks during the day!! 

Although I am strong, I have pretty good manners and don't jump up at all. If you are looking for a dog to exercise AND cuddle with, I could be your boy. I am the best of both worlds, let me show you!

animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in dog who needs a new home. Adoption can be one of the most fulfilling experiences in your life and especially in the life of your new canine companion.

A note to those looking at CPR. We have no perfect dogs - but many of our dogs have proven to be perfect for a certain someone. Our job is to find those someone's. Our most successful adopters come to CPR not because they want a dog. They come to us because they want to give a dog a home. We urge all of our potential adopters not to fall in love with a picture. While we like to know what you like in looks, a dog is more than a pretty face. Our goal is to match you with the best possible pet for you and your home. We want to create furever families.

Our descriptions contain all that we know about this dog today. We'll update as more information is known.

Are you looking to adopt within the next 30 days? If so please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and complete the application. You'll find it in the menu on the left hand side. You'll also find a total listing of all our dogs available.

Just browsing but interested in poodles and poodle mixes? Please drop a note to applications@carolinapoodlerescue.org with your name, address and phone # and email. We'll add you to our mailing list.

thanks
the CPR Adoption team

Date into Rescue: 11/2/2020

Reason for being in rescue: Bentley was abandoned, in his crate, at the door of a North Carolina shelter.
Foster location: Dreamweaver Farms, Pacolet SC
Special Needs? Bentley will be adopted on a neuter contract. Bentley appears to be neutered - there are no testicles showing but since we have no actual proof of the surgery. We're erring on the side of caution and letting you know that no documentation from a vet exists. About 10% of dogs are cryptochoid (only one testicle descends). A much smaller portion that that are double-cryptorchoid (neither testicle descends). But it does happen. In over 4,000 male dogs, we have had 2 instances of documented double cryptorchoid dogs.
Weight: 36 lbs
Height: 15 in at the shoulder
Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Adoption Fee: $349

Fence needed? Yes

What kind of home would be best for me? Fenced in yard is a must and long, long walks would be ideal. Bentley is looking for an adult person to spend his time and days with. No children under 10. He's a strong willed dog and loud noises (think children at play) would escalate him higher than he needs to go. For instance, when other dogs in his play group are running the fence, he'll snap at the other dog "get out of my face." With respectful, happy and playful dogs he's great.

He needs a dog friend - he is fearful when meeting new people without one but his dog friend will ultimately let Bentley be the boss. Sex does not matter to Bentley. What matters is the other dog is even tempered. If you want Bentley as an only dog, be prepared to be here several hours to allow him time to learn to trust you.

What is my personality like? Hyper, playful and headstrong. Bentley's terrier personality is one that is delightful to the experienced terrier person but somewhat intimidating if you don't know the breed. Bentley's inner dog says I am sassy and outgoing but his experiences have said don't trust humans.

Bentley was badly matted when he was first found and it took several weeks to allow grooming. His caregiver that he trusts stayed with the groomer and he was found as long as his comfort person was nearby and allowed shaving. Shave downs like this one hurt. Bentley's new person will recognize that hygiene has not been done as needed and will have him in regularly (I suggest every two weeks) for several months to insure that Bentley ends up loving, not fearing, the grooming process.

When introduced to cats, he was totally indifferent. He walks fairly well on a leash but needs some skills in that area. He does not know basics such as sit although we are working on those with him.

How do I act when I first meet new people? Bentley is very friendly and happy upon meeting a new person if there are other dogs around. If there are no other dogs around, he is timid at first, unsure of what is expected. He can be bribed with treats and with one of his main caregivers.

Other tips and tidbits: Bentley's estimated birthday is 10/28/2018

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

Please note - we do not ship dogs. If you are interested in adopting, please take a look at the distance between the foster home location and your location and make sure you are willing to make that trip. Most of our dogs are at our farm in Pacolet, South Carolina.

To apply, please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and visit the tab on the left that directions you to the online application.

Please note that when screening applications, we look at the entire home and then make suggestions based on what would be a good fit for your home. You are not being screened for a specific dog although we are looking to see what type of dog interests you - poodles or non poodles, color, age, etc. Others here may be a better fit for you. It is very difficult to get to know a living animal from a picture and a short description. Since we are constantly getting in new dogs, this may be a dog not in our listings yet. We want you to be very happy with your new companion and will make suggestions based on what you tell us about you.

Thank you for considering CPR.

Sweet, gentle Lara Beautiful, Sweet, Kind, came in to the shelter so scared and shut down after her Covid shut down somewhere and after the fires. We dont know her story but her face said it all and her body.
She was in shock. She has come so far. She smiles everyday now and every step is joyful for her.
She is learning to go on pack walks and loves being with other dogs. She loves anyone that has a kind gentle approach and a treat! She will smile from ear to ear and trot right along.
We think she is around 3-4 years old.
She wants to be happy and please her people.
We would like a calm home with another nice dog for company, slow walks but will go wherever you want.
Lots of love, kindness and treats, She is very special. A gentle soul.
We have video snippets of her with dogs and out walking, but no time to load them to petfinder yet.
All dog friendly! Wants to love and live life with her friend or family!
 She is about 50 pounds. Her face tells us she is a mixed breed and maybe some boxer, Shepherd. Not really sure.. 
She wants her family or person so bad. She longs to make you happy and loves to play with all dogs. She knows how to sit and simple obedience. She is completely dog friendly with both small and large dogs and probably cat friendly.  She is easy on a leash and loves her trail walks. She is incredibly loving, bright and a real star. Somebody will be very lucky to have her. 
She would love to go hiking, camping, car rides and to the beach. She is looking to see the world with her new person or family.
 
She is up to date on vaccines, spayed and micro-chipped. 
Please go to our website and fill out an application telling us why you would make her  or one of her friends a great home!

animal.description:
Covie came into rescue as an owner surrender. Her owner passed away and the son wouldn't take care of her. She was living outside even after an accident that left her paralyzed and unable to use her back legs. She was living outside thru 2 hurricane and a tropical storm. 

We immediately sent someone to go get her. She didn't know these people but ran from the son to their vehicle and jumped right in. She is the most kind gentle loving dog. She just wants to be loved. 

We are uncertain exactly what happened to her to cause this injury. She had never seen a vet for medical treatment after her injury. We took her to our vet and started her on some injections and we started water therapy. Covie is so determined to walk. She is now standing on her own without our help and will take a few steps. She needs a family that will continue to help her build her muscles in her back legs. We are going to start laser therapy with her very soon. She does have a wheelchair that comes with her. She loves to go for walks. 

However she would absolutely love to just cuddle on the floor or couch with some help up. 

Covie is good with other dogs that are respectful of her space and more laid back. She is not good with cats. She is also good with kids but we feel a home with older kids is best. She is spayed, up to date on shots, microchipped and on heartworm prevention. 

To apply for Covie go to www.caninehavenrescue.org under available adoptions tab. Her adoption fee is $200

animal.description:
Olive is an adorable shy little gal. We received a call to catch a stray dog that was severly emaciated out in the middle of nowhere by some woods. So after 3 hours on scene we were finally able to catch her. It was obvious that she had pups recently. We walked her around looking and searching for puppies. No pups were found. We took her right to a vet to see what they thought. He thought that pups had already been weaned and someone dumped momma. We took her home and got her settled for the night. 

The next day we had to go pick up dogs out of town. Before we left we spent time with Olive. We did her shots and loved on her. But something in her eyes said something was off. 4 hours into our trip we called the neighbor to go get her and our 25 ft lead. We told her exactly where to take her. We just felt there were puppies out there. We also called for others to go help search. When Olive got out of the vehicle she took off running. She led them right to where her 4 tiny pups were hidden way up inside a brush pile. The pups were only about 48 hours old and had been without mom for 24 of that. Everyone was fine and the pups have homes of their own. Now its Olives turn for a forever home where she will be loved and not thrown out like trash.

She is good with other dogs big and small. She is also good with cats and kids. She is up to date on shots, rabies, and will be spayed at the end of the month. She is also microchipped and heartworm negative and on prevention. Her adoption fee is $300. To adopt go to www.caninehavenrescue.org under available adoptions tab.

animal.description:
This is Chance. He is a handsome young male, 1-2 years old, mix, weighing about 40lbs. There is a little bit of hound, certainly seen in his body and tail, with a boxy, solid head, like a St. Bernhard, only a little smaller. He has beautiful white short fur with back spots, and great looking black/white coloring on his face. Safe to say he is a good old all-American mutt.

Chance has had a little bit of a rough start and wasnt treated well and ended up in a kennel in Southern Missouri. Rescue groups descended on the kennel that Chance was in, taking all the other dogs. Chance would have been the last dog there except we decided to give Chance a chance, and boy are we glad we did!!!

Chance is housebroken and very smart. He has had a little bit of training and, we feel, would do very well with more. He is still young and full of energy. He loves walks, playing fetch with a ball, and playing with other dogs. That said, he does do well with other dogs. He is a snuggler, loves to sit with you, or on your lap. He is also a kisser, so be ready for that. He is kennel trained and spends nights there. Not sure how he would do around cats. It's also best if Chance has no kids in the home, as he is startled by them, and unsure of their next move which makes him uncomfortable and nervous.

He has really latched on the adult human male in his foster home. Because of this, we feel he would do best with a male in the home, maybe an active guy who wants to take his doggie everywhere with him! He is nervous around new people, visitors who come over to his house, and it does take him a while to warm up to anyone new. Because of this, he will need someone with lots of patience to give him and lots of time to settle in, utlizing some training techniques to help him adopt. He is easily startled by load noises and surprises; and will approach cautiously when you reassure him that everything is okay. He is still a little nervous on car rides but settles down with positive attention.

animal.description:
Breed: Pit Bull/Mastiff mix
Sex: Male
DOB: ~12/04/2019
Weight: 65 lbs
Energy Level: Medium
Personality Type: Sweet, Active, Friendly, Protective
History: Transferred from animal control/Stray
Good With: Dogs
Fence Requirements: Required
Ideal Home: Active home! No apartments please.
Special Info: Already housebroken and knows ""sit""! Please note, Starsky's adopter will receive one FREE session with our trainer, included in his adoption fee.

The information we are providing for this animal was developed based on observations and assessments in a shelter or foster environment. We do our best to provide information that will help determine if the dog might be a good fit for you. Please note that behaviors may change in a home environment. We also ask our applicants to assume that any animal they adopt from us will need to be potty trained and learn house manners, although this is not always the case. Our online animal bios are designed to provide as much information as possible and answer some anticipated questions. We do not have the resources to respond to emails with more specific questions.

We are receiving an unusually high number of applications per pet at this time! Please follow the rules below to ensure your application is reviewed; pay attention closely to these instructions because applications will NOT be processed if they are not followed. Please keep in mind that dog/cat availability is currently changing by the hour; you will receive an email if the animal you are interested in is no longer available. New dogs become available almost every day, so feel free to let us know if someone else interests you if your initial choice is already adopted! 

Fill out the application (DOG: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/IHD-DOG-Application-9-10-18.pdf, CAT: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/IHD-CAT-Application.pdf) completely. Every question must be answered, and it must be signed. If you are going to type your responses, open the application, save it, type your answers, and save it again. 

-Applicants must be 21+ years old and live within a 50-mile radius of our shelter at 22415 Groesbeck Hwy, Warren 48089.

-You must identify at least 1 dog/cat that you are interested in. If there are multiple dogs/cats, number them in order of priority. 

-Scan a copy of proof of home ownership (i.e. tax bill, deed, or mortgage payment - you can black out the account #, etc.) or animal clause/agreement of your rental agreement.

-Attach the application and home ownership proof/rental agreement animal clause to a new email and send it to bark@iheartdogs.org. The subject line must be formatted to read ""#1 choice of dog/cat, Your First and Last Name"". Example: Subject: Fido, Jane Doe
Once your application is received, it will be assigned to an Adoption Counselor who will follow-up with the applicant who is the best fit within a few days, or to discuss other dogs/cats. It could take up to a couple of weeks for you to receive a final disposition on your application so there is no need to check on the status.

-Introductions will be scheduled by appointment only, 45 minutes per appointment. The entire household, including current dogs, must be present for the appointment. The introductions will take place outside in our parking lot.

-We will continue to perform vet checks for current and prior pets in the household.

-Home visits will be in person for the yard and virtual for inside the home.

-Finalizing the adoption will also be scheduled by appointment.

While this process may seem cumbersome, it is interim during COVID-19, and it is designed to help us respond to the volume of emails we receive every day. Since we are receiving a high volume of applications, please be patient if a dog/cat is no longer available. 

Thank you for your understanding.

1020068

I need a single family home with a fenced in yard since I require lots of physical and mental stimulation!

Bogart is a sweet 1 year old Shepherd mix and is 100% house trained. He is super playful, he will throw his own toys and chase after them. Hes also very loving, he prefers to be within 5 feet of his human at all times, laying at my feet while I work. He is curious about shoes or other items he finds and will quickly give them over and go back to his toys. Our Chihuahua is not welcoming but he tries to play with her anyway, I imagine he would do well with any dog that would want to play. He needs a home without cats.

animal.description:
****Please do not send us inquiries/emails asking if this dog is still available; if a dog/puppy is still listed on Petfinder, we are still accepting applications for them. See the bottom of this bio for more FAQs regarding our adoption process before emailing.****

Name: Jagger 2 & Jada

Age: 6-7 years

Current Weight: 50-60 pounds

Rescued from: Texas

Jada and Jagger were rescued from an area where there is an abundance of homeless dogs, and not a lot of shelter space for them to go while they wait for their forever homes. They will be arriving at SNARR's Adoption Center in Brewster, NY on December 18, 2020 ready for adoption!

This friendly duo was saved from becoming just another pair of owner surrendered dogs in an over-crowded Texas shelter when SNARR agreed to help.  Jagger and Jada are house-trained, great with kids and just great all around pups.  They have lived in the same home with each other and it's apparent they love to be with each other, so we didn't have the heart to separate them.  They need to find a home together with a fenced in yard for them to enjoy the great outdoors, chase squirrels, sun bath and just run free.  Both dogs are very sweet, Jada is a little timid at first and definitely feels more confident and comfortable when Jagger is with her.  You may notice that Jagger sits a little funny that is due to a plate installed to repair his leg when he was younger.  These darling souls are looking for a wonderful family that will enjoy taking them on neighborhood walks and hiking at the local park.  If you are looking for two wonderful dogs to love, spoil and take on adventures, maybe Jada and Jagger are your perfect duo.    

Health: up to date on required vaccines

Adoption fee: $700

IMPORTANT: Jada has not yet been altered. For any dog or puppy that is not able to be spayed/neutered prior to adoption, SNARR requires a $125 deposit in addition to your adoption fee, as well as a signed Spay/Neuter Contract stating you will have this dog altered within 6 months of adoption. The $125 deposit will be returned once the contract has been fulfilled. 

To apply to adopt Jagger & Jada, fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. 
**Meet and greets will not be scheduled without an approved application.**

-------------------------------------------------------
FAQs -- PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING

**Please note that SNARR NE is a volunteer-based organization. While our volunteers will try to respond to you as quickly as possible, it is helpful if you review the following information about our adoption process before emailing:**

- LISTED BREED(S) & AGE: We are taking our best guess on age, breed, and size when fully grown, based on the puppy's/dog's physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. *NOTE* We rarely know a dog's exact age, nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. Because we often do not have access to medical records at the time that we are posting dogs to Petfinder, there are sometimes discrepancies between what is posted on Petfinder and what might be listed on a dog's medical records.

- SNARR'S ADOPTION PROCESS: The first step in adopting or meeting a SNARR dog/puppy is to fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. Once we receive your application, one of our adoption application processors will contact you, review our adoption process with you, and answer any additional questions you may have. **We do not go on a first-come-first-serve basis for adoptions, but on best fit for a family and most importantly the puppy or dog.**

- MEETING ADOPTABLE DOGS: Meet and greets will not be scheduled until after your adoption application has been fully processed by one of our adoption processors.

- APPLYING ONLINE: If you fill out an online application, please do so from a computer (not a mobile device), make sure you answer ALL the questions in as much detail as possible, and that you receive a confirmation email. If you do not receive a confirmation email, that means we did NOT receive your application.

- PUPPIES: We do suggest listing a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several litter mates.

- ADOPTION FEES:  $495 for puppies / $375 for adults. Adoption Fees for Seniors, Special Needs and Bonded Pairs vary

animal.description: Hi! I'm Taco! I'm a super friendly and playful guy. I have LOTS of energy and love to play with toys, especially with rope toys. I know how to sit, and I am working on stay and shake. I love everyone, so much that sometimes I can't contain my excitement. I do "play bite" and can get mouthy when I'm excited. I really need a patient adopter who can help me with my manners, I need to learn arms are not toys and how to walk nicely on a leash. I'm only 9 months old, so I'm still a puppy and really need a home that is willing to work with me. I have done well with other energetic dogs who love to play. I probably have too much energy for a cat, though. I think kids are awesome, but I might accidentally knock them over or play rough with them until I learn better. If you are an active person or family in need of a goofball, please apply for me!

All of our dogs come spayed/neutered, fully vaccinated with proof, microchipped, 4Dx tested (basic blood work that tests for diseases), currently on monthly preventatives, and dewormed with a board spectrum dewormer.

animal.description:
To be considered for adopting a dog from Canine Lifeline, you must have an approved application must be on file. Please visit http://www.caninelifeline.org/adoption-process/ for more information about our adoption process and to submit an online application.

Sweet Pea is a gorgeous 6 year-old Aussie/Border Collie mix spayed female with a fluffy bobtail who was surrendered to an overcrowded county dog shelter by her owner along with another Border Collie mix named Spicy after she had to move to an assisted living facility and couldn't take the dogs with her. Both dogs made the trip to Canine Lifeline so they could take their time finding great new forever homes. While they may have lived together peacefully in the past, we quickly discovered upon their arrival that Sweet Pea and Spicy no longer want to have anything to do with each other. Perhaps the stress of all the recent changes in their life has taken its toll on their relationship, but they will need to go to separate new homes. Sweet Pea is also unpredictable around other dogs so does need to go to a home where she'll be an only dog. . Sweet Pea is a very sensitive girl whose world has been turned upside down and she's trying very hard to process all the recent changes in her life. She was very skittish when she first arrived here with us. She is still head shy and apprehensive when we slip a leash over her head so not sure if something happened to her in the past that makes her wary of that type of movement. She's beginning to trust us now and once she's in a quiet place away from other dogs, she loves to snuggle up with her new human friends and enjoys being petted and loved. The shelter told us that Sweet Pea is cat-aggressive so will need a kitty-free home. She's been a little nervous on a leash so is going to need a home in a rural area or very quiet neighborhood so she can relax and enjoy life. A yard with a secure aboveground fence is also required for her. Busy urban or high-density suburban living would be terrifying for her. We know there's a kind person or family out there who can make the world right again for Sweet Pea and we look forward to seeing her get the chance to relax and settle into her new forever home. Sweet Pea weighs about 48 pounds and her adoption fee is $325. She's spayed, heartworm negative and on monthly preventative, up to date on vaccinations including bivalent canine influenza, wormed, on flea and tick preventative, and microchipped. As part of the adoption process, all adopters must commit to a two-week adjustment period to make sure it's a great match before the adoption is finalized. Please email info@caninelifeline.org if you're interested in Sweet Pea. An approved application is required before we schedule meets with any of our dogs. Please note that we don't place our dogs in homes with children under 7 years of age. We correspond via email so please check your junkmail or spam folder to make sure our reply hasn't landed in there. Please visit our website at www.caninelifeline.org to see more photos of Sweet Pea and to submit an online application if you live in Northeast OH.
animal.name: Sweet Pea

animal.description:
Please only send inquires to the email in this bio all others will not be answered. Please read the bio before sending questions - we answer all we know about the dog here.

Hi there! My name is Harry but everyone always greets me with "Hi, Handsome" . People are always fussing over my big head and beautiful coat but I don't mind because this involves lots of pets and belly rubs!

I'm only 3 years old so I'm a lot of fun and I will keep you laughing all day long. People say I am a BIG boy (I don't see it) ...sometimes I don't know my own strength and may walk with my weight, but I'm a quick learner!

I am a unique breed called Leonberger mix known for being super sweet, loyal, and reminiscent of a majestic lion . I love to go on walks and introduce myself to everyone on the sidewalk (sometimes I even roll over at strangers feet just so they rub my belly) but as soon as we get home I like to lay down at (on) my humans feet.

I am house broken, I never bark, and I do great in the car!! I am also super smart and know a lot of commands like sit, down, and shake. I was alone on my own for awhile, so now all I want to do is stay by my human as much as I can. I get sad and a little anxious when everyone leaves but I'm sure once I find my forever family, it'll just take me a bit to adjust and trust that you aren't leaving me.

I'd love to find my furever home! I am still young with lots and lots of love to give. If you are ready for snuggles and telling me I am handsome all day long, let me know! Can't wait to meet you you.

He can be dog selective...we're not sure about cats or small children...mature older children should be okay. Harry is neutered/microchipped, vaccinated & on Flea & Heartworm preventative.

Harry's Adoption fee is $400 - obedience training is required after adoption.

Obedience training is also required for all our pups. We understand with what is going on in the world that this may be a bit delayed. Please email us the completion certificate.

To apply to foster or adopt please fill out application at

www.heidislegacydogrescue.com/apply-to-foster-or-adopt

Thank you for completing the application. We are all volunteers and short on time, we will contact you back only if we have more questions or your application is approved and you will be invited to meet the dog. We apologize for not being able to answer everyone back.

For more information contact Kelly.V@HeidisLegacyDogRescue.com

DOGS are in Foster Homes. There is NO shelter.

**Our companions MUST live in your home as part of your family.**We do not transport.

**See our website for more information. www.HeidisLegacyDogRescue.com

All communication is thru email so please be patient with us. We are all volunteers and work full time jobs and have families of our own.

It takes anywhere between 3-7 days to process an application - the more complete the application the easier it is for us to process it. Please notify your vet that we will be contacting them and to release information to us.

ADOPTION PROCESS:

1. Complete this application
www.heidislegacydogrescue.com/apply-to-foster-or-adopt

***Everyone must submit an application - we only keep them on file for 1 month

2. Application background check, vet check, etc

3. Invitation thru email to meet the dog(s).

4. Adoption Contract

animal.description:
Adult home only (18+), no cats, experienced dog owners only

 Ideal home: Hey! I am Aslan. Boy, am I handsome.. at least that’s what I hear. I am a little over 5 years old and am a Doberman mix. My family surrendered me here because I was not fitting into their new lifestyle. I lived with them for the last 4 years of my life, so you can imagine how I am feeling. Initially, I do take time to trust new people. I’ve warmed up to the some of the staff here and improve every day! I am quite smart, know lots of commands and am affectionate once I get comfortable. I even sport this pink get up so great! I am strong and can be reactive towards other dogs at first, so I will need a strong handler. I would do best in an adult only home, one that isn’t too chaotic. My last home was, so I am sure that took a mental toll on me at times. I am anxious, but again a sweetheart. I like to chase tennis balls and will bring them back! Though reactive towards the dogs I have met here, I do well once I am used to the dog. I was off leash with a few here, just hung out and enjoyed the company. I would do best with a dog that isn’t so pushy or be your only pet! No cats for me either, wasn’t too fond of them in my last home. It might take us a few meetings for me to feel okay, so please be patient with me! I have went through a lot like my other shelter friends have, but I just need time to get to know you. I will need an experienced dog family, adjusting to a new environment might be a challenge for me and could use a family that’ll help me transition stress free!
 
Aslan is neutered, chipped and UTD on vaccinations. Please apply to:
https://www.humanesocietyhbg.org/adopt/dog-adoption-application-online/

animal.description:
MEET EGGPLANT!!

Underdog Rescue does not physically have this dog in its possession. For more information, please email: amy.farner@gmail.com.

To visit with this pup, please make an appointment here: https://mcaccappointments.as.me/adopt. NOTE: People who sign up for these appointments often no-show. We have been told that you can go straight to the shelter and let them know you are there to meet this particular dog. From what we understand, the shelter will squeeze you in except between 12-3PM and near the 6PM closing time. (Please know this is not a guarantee). If the dog is at risk, please ask for a supervisor to meet that particular dog. We hope your adoption process is smooth and full of happiness!

Eggplant is such a fun dog that loves to go for a walk. He pulls a little at first because he's so happy to get out of his kennel but calms down quickly and walks very nicely. He likes to check in regularly with the volunteer who is walking him. It takes a little while to walk Eggplant because he loves to sniff everything! He likes the play yard and takes treats gently. He is an affectionate boy who loves to give kisses. And, he's potty trained! Eggplant would be better in a home with older children and as an only dog. He should not be taken to a dog park.

Eggplant is an older dog that still has some spring in his step! If you think Eggplant would be a good fit in your home, please come and meet him today!

This amazing pup is currently located at Maricopa County Animal Care & Control, Animal ID Number A4439018.

*Please Note: This animal is courtesy posted for the Maricopa County Shelter; UNDERDOG RESCUE DOES NOT HAVE THIS DOG. MCACC is located at 2500 S. 27th Avenue, Phoenix. Different adoption fees/policy may apply. Please visit MCACC's website http://www.maricopa.gov/pets/locations.aspx for hours. You may also wish to call 602-506-7387 (PETS) and provide the animal's A# above to verify is still available.

animal.description:
These brothers strayed up to the rescuer's home, looking for a safe place.  Sadly, the family has 3 dogs and couldn't take them all in for their own.  They arrived with Nimbus and her 3 puppies, so adding 6 new dogs wasn't in their best interest.  

With a guesstimated birthday in Nov. 2019, these boys are hesitant in new experiences.  They're very intelligent and affectionate so are learning at an astonishing rate.  They've captured their foster mom's heart, but she also knows that being in a big dog pack isn't as rewarding as having their own forever families.

Buzz has excellent leash-manners.  He is content in his crate overnight and doesn't make a mess.  He rides well in a car, but is nervous so must be helped in.  When taken on walks in public, he looks to his handler for reassurance in stressful situations.

He is eager to please, once he is comfortable with his people and the environment.  He's house-trained when kept on a regular schedule.  Currently that is a potty break every 2 hours.  There are cats in his foster home, but he doesn't seem to pay attention to them, being more interested in his doggy friends.

April 2020:  We are not holding public adoption events at this time.  Qualified families are being invited to appointments to meet specific dogs.  There are currently no opportunities to view multiple dogs and adoption events aren't being held at Tractor Supply in Lenoir.

Whether dogs / puppies come in as strays or owner surrenders, we usually have to make our best guess as to birthdate and breed.   

If adopted into a home with other animals, particularly cats, your new pet should be crated or secured when you're not available to supervise to insure a harmonious relationship.  

A vet reference is required to confirm responsible pet ownership.  We suggest first time pet owners look for an adult dog for companionship and to gain experience through another rescue or your local government-run animal control..

Adoption fee covers two vaccinations plus spay / neuter if using our local low-cost spay/neuter clinic (overnight stay required) and surgery occurs as agreed upon in the adoption contract.  Convenience fee equal to refundable spay/neuter deposit may be added if using our veterinarian.  Additional fees for 3rd puppy vaccination, refundable spay/neuter deposit, etc. may apply.  

We are an all-volunteer, foster-based rescue.  We receive no funding from agencies.  Available animals can be seen most Saturdays at Tractor Supply in Lenoir from 10:00 a.m. to 2:00 p.m.  We recommend interested parties contact us to pre-qualify for adoption so their new furry family can go home once paperwork is complete.  Fees are required in cash.  For more information on our organization, our website is www.petpartnersrescue.org.

This hunk is Flex!
He knows he's handsome!
His one eye is half ice blue.
His markings are gorgeous.  
We are told he is 7 years old and does great with small children. He's non-reactive to dogs but meet & greet would be required as usual.  
Due to his size he might be intimidating to a cat. 
He's solid and on the large side.
His owner moved & surrendered him to the shelter.

He does have good manners, don't get us wrong, he's fantastic we are just warning if you aren't strong enough to walk a strong dog maybe  a different dog would be a better choice.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Snuggle (SC) is a female Black Mouth Cur/Shepherd mix rescued in South Carolina. Our veterinary partner estimates Snuggle is 2 years old at time of intake in December 2020. Snuggle is good with people of all ages and other dogs, but she is not a fan of cats. Unbelievably, Snuggle was left outside with her puppies, tied to a tree as her owners moved out. They just left her there, tied up, to fend for herself and her puppies. Not surprisingly, 4 of Snuggle's 10 puppies have passed away. Snuggle has experienced unimaginable cruelty, but now that she's a Rescue Dogs Rock NYC pup, we will head her in the right direction towards a happy life! Snuggle has 4 human foster siblings and she is fantastic with them. After settling in, she is playing well with her foster doggy sibling. Snuggle is calm and appreciates leisure. She is housetrained and is working on her manners. She only barks appropriately, and since she doesn't appreciate cats, she believes that barking at cats is appropriate! Snuggle seeks out affection and will nudge your hand to be petted. She is happy to play if you want to; if not, she is totally okay sitting in your lap or lying in bed. If you would like to be the happy in the rest of Snuggle's life, please apply online to adopt Snuggle (SC) at www.rescuedogsrocknyc.org.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website. Milton's previous owner could not care for him anymore, so they dropped him off at a shelter. Milton is with us now, safe and sound. He is incredibly sweet and well behaved. He is a happy boy who loves to play with other dogs. Milton went home with Judy. He is walking around the house laying on the couch , running around the yard, so a fenced yard is required . Sleeping in the crate no problem, rode well in the car, He will make a great addition to a loving family. He is currently heartworm positive, but please do not let that shy you away from this wonderful dog! Pet Rescue By Judy practices the slow kill method for treating heartworm, and we have had great success with it. The slow kill method means we give the infected dog a medication for 30 days (if you adopt within his first 30 days we will provide you with the medication) and then after that all he needs is his monthly topical of Advantage Multi.
Please fill out an application to meet this wonderful dog!

We cannot hold dogs, please submit your application when you are ready to adopt. PLEASE READ THE FOLLOWING PARAGRAPHS FOR INFORMATION ON THIS DOG, AS WELL AS INFORMATION ON OUR PROCESS.

Juno is around 1-2 yrs old and weighs 17 pounds. He was rescued as a stray. He has a calm temperament And enjoys the company of others - human and canine. He enjoys being pet and is easy to handle. He does not object to being picked up if need be. Please submit an adoption application if you would like to meet Juno by visiting our website, poochmatch.com. Open the ADOPTION folder at the top of our home page. Just fill in the blanks and return it via email to poochmatch@hotmail.com. We receive many applications for a single dog, however only one prospective adopter will be invited to meet and adopt Juno.

His adoption fee is $350 which covers the cost of his neuter, all core vaccines (Rabies and Distemper/Parvo), microchip and microchip registration. The first step is completing an application which is available on our website, poochmatch.com, under the adoption tab. Please read the below paragraphs for more information on our process.

UPDATE: ADOPTION EVENTS CANCELLED DUE TO PANDEMIC AND SOCIAL DISTANCING. If you are interested in meeting any Poochmatch dog at our weekly adoption event on Saturdays at the Petsmart in Yorba Linda, CA (5521 Mirage St.) between 1-5 PM, please fill out an application from our website, poochmatch.com, and submit it no later than 11 AM on Fridays. Upon receipt AND approval, the dog you are interested in meeting will be made available to meet on a Saturday. Due to the high volume of dogs and puppies in our foster homes, it is impossible to bring them all every Saturday. The only way to ensure that the dog that you are interested in will be at the adoption event is to FILL OUT AN APPLICATION AND BE APPROVED. Otherwise, we cannot guarantee that the dog you are interested in will be at our adoption event. If you cannot make the time frame of our events, appointments can be made at another time and location solely at the discretion of the foster parent. Please understand that private appointments will be coordinated to meet the convenience of the foster parent/transporter.

All adoption fees cover the mandatory and non-negotiable spay/neuter, rabies, microchip, microchip registration, full sets of core vaccinations (rabies and 1 set of distemper/parvo for adults, 4 for puppies) and deworming. Adoption fees vary based on age, breed, size and the costs incurred on the dog's behalf by us i.e. medical, behavioral training, etc. and they range from $225-$495.


COVID-19 PROCEDURE:
In an effort to create a safe environment for our potential adopters and our staff, we have changed our protocols and procedures during these difficult times. Starting immediately, our procedures will change from what’s written on our website and other social media platforms. Our weekly adoption event at the Petsmart in Yorba Linda is temporarily cancelled due to COVID-19 and social distancing. The only way to meet one of the dogs/puppies we have available for adoption is through completion of our adoption application through our website, poochmatch.com, before 11 AM on Fridays. On Fridays when we review the applications, we will pick the best fit for each dog or puppy applied for and coordinate mutually agreeable appointment times for the applicants who are approved that week. Private appointments are currently only scheduled on Wednesday, Thursday or Saturday of each week. Masks or bandanas are mandatory; faces must be properly covered.

With the overwhelming desire of the public to adopt at this time, we have received as many as 30 applications for one dog in just one week. Working with a staff of volunteers, we are only able to reach out on Fridays to the people we have approved to adopt. If you have not heard from us by Friday, we have selected a different applicant. If you have multiple dogs/puppies that you are interested in, please indicate each dog/puppy of interest on the application at that time so we don’t rule you out for another dog/puppy available for adoption.

Please understand, we have an influx of texts, phone calls and emails that makes it impossible to get to each and every one of you. Not just for adoption interest, but also from veterinarians, people who must relinquish dogs, people who have found a stray dog in need of pick up, etc. We are currently not in need of fosters. Due to the fact that there is such a high demand, we are sticking with strict protocol to not adopt out of Southern California. We apologize for this inconvenience and difficulty to be able to get in touch with us while there is an overwhelming desire and demand to adopt at this time. We appreciate your understanding and patience as we navigate through these difficult times with every intention to keep the public and our staff safe.

Hecter is a great little dog that loves attention. He gets along great with other dogs and loves to play.

Hecter has a history of growling and nipping kids that play too rough so we recommend kids over 12 years old. Hecter needs a family with small dog experience that will start from day one in training him that it's not okay to growl and nip. His biggest concern is with crates. He loves to sleep in them, but becomes very territorial when in a crate and will bite.

Fill out an application at the link below. Find the dog/cat you are interested in and click the adopt button. That will take you to an application. Once approved you will be called for an appointment to meet your possible new family member, or at that time you can meet the other animals as well. https://petstablished.com/public/search/shelter/301551

Adoption fee is $150 which includes, spay/neuter, vaccines, etc, and a free 1 year membership to our 5 acre ARF Park. For other dog questions please email ARFdogs74006@gmail.com

We do adopt out of state, but the adopter must travel to ARF to meet the dog they are looking to adopt. They must have an approved application before traveling to meet the dog. We do allow small dogs that are eligible to fly in the cabin of a plane. We DO NOT allow dogs to travel in the cargo area of the plane under any circumstances. Any dog that is adopted can of course go by personal vehicle. We do not allow dogs to be transported "pony express style" where they are passed from driver to driver.

animal.description:
Orion has a new joy of life called a pig squeaky toy that lights up his life and brings him to life! He will do just about anything to hear a squeak or get to play with it and it has him prancing along beside us on our walks and allowing us to pet and interact with him more. His fun side has peaked through and it is great to watch him blossom and come to life!

Orion is a fellow looking for a kind, gentle and patient person who will help guide him along through his journey of becoming a pet. Orion came to the shelter several months ago scared and untrusting and although he has made lots of progress, Orion still needs a guardian angel to help him through his journey. He is a pretty stoic and self contained boy, so you will not see a bunch of emotion emanating from him. He hangs back and observes everything! Orion has spent the last 2 weeks in a foster home and is house trained, crate trained, tolerant of the small dogs, playful with big dogs and would love a female dog his size to play with. He will be happiest with a big fenced yard and space to hang outside in a very quite neighborhood, but is fine to follow you around the house too! 

Please email the behavioral team at kheadlee@wenatcheehumane.org with some information about you living situation and a phone number.

animal.description:
Sky is being fostered in NY.

What Sky's foster mom has to say about Sky:
will be spayed on Jan 19, 2021
Sky is a MAJOR cuddler. She is one of the sweetest dogs I have ever met. She will follow you around all day and lay by your feet or stand there waiting for what you'll do next. Because of her level of blindness, she gets anxious/agitated when you're not around, so she will whine and urinate if left alone for too long. She loves to just lie ON YOU and get rubbed, and she'll also jump up on you as much as you let her and just "hug" and "kiss" you. She sleeps in her own bed in our bedroom but isn't territorial at all. You can kinda just nudge her out of the way, and she's like "ok, what's next?" Her personality is always happy/curious. She never wants to be alone so she'll pitter/patter around. She is a great walker and has no issues being on leash. She is fantastic with my other dog and they have normal dog spats where they each have their own space but never aggressive. She rarely barks except when feels threatened or anxious. She also has a fantastic memory and counts steps/stairs with increasing accuracy so she knows exactly how to navigate outside, down the porch stairs and back up again.
She is a concern for an older individual because she will follow and lay behind you when you're standing so there is risk of tripping.

The Animal Rescue Project (www.animalrescueproject.org) is committed to the best possible veterinary care for the pets it rescues and it is looking for adopters who will be similarly committed.

All dogs and puppies are given a general check-up when they enter our program. They receive medication to remove any intestinal parasites (worms), fleas, and ticks they may have. Dogs greater than six months of age are checked for heartworm. If heartworm positive, the Animal Rescue Project treats the disease. Dogs and pups receive all age-appropriate vaccinations for distemper, and dogs greater than four months of age are also vaccinated for rabies, in compliance with State of Michigan laws. All dogs will be microchipped as well.

Most dogs and older puppies are spayed or neutered before adoption. In the case of puppies not old enough to be safely sterilized, a $50 deposit is required at the time of adoption and is refunded to the adopter with proof of sterilization.

The Animal Rescue Project requires every adopter to establish an active relationship with a veterinarian no later than 10 days after adoption. Adopters will receive a plan for routine veterinary care at the time of adoption and are expected to work with their vet to complete the plan.

animal.description:
Hiiiii! My name is Chaplin aka Chappy! I am a 2 year old Dogo Argentino that is looking to find my forever home! I’m a big goofball and still working on my manners.

It would be best for my new family to continue training with a professional as I’m really silly and kind of a clown.

I recently completed my heart worm treatment and now slowly I am getting exposed to more things. I seem to be interested in cats but a proper introduction may be best. I am around other dogs but seem to do better with lady dogs.

I’m working on my introductions with people as I’m kind of judgey.. some people I just love right away others I need to be around you for a little bit. I’m not aggressive just vocalize my opinion.

I seem to warm up to woman quickly but some men I want to get to know more over a little bit of time. I am an awesome eater and do not turn down my food or snacks. I am a giant love bug and looking for someone who likes to be active but also spends time as a homebody. If you’re not looking to adopt, please share me so my new family can find me!

My perfect home would have a big fenced in yard for me to play in, and no kids under 10 years old - I'm just too clumsy and I wouldn't want to knock anyone down!

Dogos are a wonderful breed but we urge anyone interested to dig in and do a lot of research before deciding if they are a good fit for your home. They require a lot of attention and training with them never ends!  Boundaries must be enforced and they often need reminders as they push past boundaires you set! Dogos are loving, kind and gentle but don't mistake that for weakness because they are equally powerful and intense as well! Everyone in the home must be on board with having a dogo and play a major role in their daily routines and training. Yes it is work, but the rewards are ten-fold! Lazy homes don't work for dogos as they need stimulation, exercise, and lots of attention too during their younger years.  Our goal in rescue is to be as transparent as we can about each and every dog plus make sure new families really understand the needs of a dogo!
